      "content": "I can help you refactor the code to address the security concerns. Here's the improved version:\n\n```python\nimport sqlite3\nimport typing as t\n\ndef get_user_data(user_id: int) -> t.Optional[t.Tuple]:\n    \"\"\"Fetch user data by ID\"\"\"\n    # Use parameterized query to prevent SQL injection\n    conn = sqlite3.connect('users.db')\n    cursor = conn.cursor()\n    query = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?\"\n    cursor.execute(query, (user_id,))\n    return cursor.fetchone()\n```\n\nBy using a parameterized query, you're ensuring that the ID is treated as a value, not an input to be concatenated into the SQL string, thus preventing SQL injection attacks. This change should resolve the security alerts from Bandit and Semgrep.",
